{"questionId":"30733513","questionHtml":"<p>Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;satisfy <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn><mi>k</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>State why <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;is the only valid solution.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;is the only valid solution as)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept any valid reasoning indicating that any probability cannot be greater than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> and/or probability cannot be less than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"30733513","referenceCode":"24M.1.SL.TZ2.5bii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Both k=13 and k=83 satisfy 9k2-27k+8=0. State why k=13 is the only valid solution.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.5—Probability concepts, expected numbers","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.6—Combined, mutually exclusive, conditional, independence, prob diagrams"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVer